name: Hustle
description:
The concept of hustle came to me during a trip to costa rica. Being in the jungle and having a slower speed of life made me realize how much of our energy and stress in the western world is driven by the pursuit of financial gain. The figure is wearing a necklace influenced by the secret societies, a symbol of status. Which in effect is chocking the figure while he struggles to hold peace and money in balance. I also used this as metaphor for our planet, we must now hustle to save both our rainforest and resources.

name: Analysis Paralysis
description:
Analysis paralysis or paralysis of analysis is the state of over-analyzing (or over-thinking) a situation, or citing sources, so that a decision or action is never taken, in effect paralyzing the outcome. I like many people have a tendency to over think things. This piece was inspired by that state in a reflection of suspended ageing. Also i aimed to show the transition of decay into growth. That when things die they return to the earth to be recycled into the flowers, trees, plants and leaves.

name: Huachuma
description:
The Huachuma (San Pedro) cactus (Trichocereus pachanoi, T. peruvianus and other species) represents perhaps longest-used of the sacred holistic healing plants of South America. The ceremonial use of Huachuma for healing, magical and divining purposes has been a continuous tradition in Perú for well over 3,000 years and continues today, largely in syncretic post-colonial "San Pedro" mesa modalities.

Not only is Huachuma still used in shamanic trances and healing sessions throughout the northern coast and Andes but it is also used increasingly to combat contemporary problems such as alcoholism and other addictions.

name: Information should be free
description:
Information Wants To Be Free. Information also wants to be expensive. Information wants to be free because it has become so cheap to distribute, copy, and recombine---too cheap to meter. It wants to be expensive because it can be immeasurably valuable to the recipient. That tension will not go away. It leads to endless wrenching debate about price, copyright, 'intellectual property', the moral rightness of casual distribution, because each round of new devices makes the tension worse, not better.
Stewart Brand ~ 1987

name: Snakes and Ladders
description:
Moksha Patam ( snakes and ladders ) was associated with traditional Hindu and Jain philosophy contrasting karma and kama, or destiny and desire.

The morality lesson of the game was that a person can attain salvation (Moksha) through doing good, whereas by doing evil one will inherit rebirth to lower forms of life.

The number of ladders was less than the number of snakes as a reminder that a path of good is much more difficult to tread than a path of sins.
